# Phase 5 — Scale (Tier 3), API, and Localization

**Goal:** Now that the domain has authority and engagement signals, responsibly release the programmatic conversion pages, ship the paid API, and open new-language markets.

**Why now:** Tier-3 dimension pages launched on day one would have sandboxed a fresh domain. Released onto an established, trusted site in monitored batches, they're a legitimate long-tail play.

### Architecture & infra
- Build the Tier-3 conversion page generator (`/convert/[from]-to-[to]`), each rendering a real working conversion tool (not just a number) with unique-enough surrounding context.
- Ship the paid API as a separate edge service: ratio/nearest/resize endpoints, API keys, rate limiting, usage metering, simple pricing, docs.
- Implement i18n routing, locale sitemaps, and hreflang. Translate the (small) on-page text per locale.

### Design & UX
- Design the API landing + docs experience.
- Design the language switcher and verify the design system holds across longer translated strings.
- Ensure conversion pages still feel like tools, not filler.

### Content & SEO
- Release Tier-3 pages in small monitored batches: publish, watch indexation/impressions, keep winners, prune or consolidate non-performers after ~6 months. Promote a page from `noindex` to indexable only when it demonstrably has demand + a working tool.
- Localize the highest-demand languages first (let the language_switch event and search data pick them).
- Maintain the sitemap index split (tools/guides/locales) as volume grows.

### Analytics & QA
- Track per-batch Tier-3 performance; enforce the prune rule.
- Track API signups/usage; monitor localized-page performance separately per locale.

### Monetization & growth
- API becomes a recurring revenue stream uncorrelated with SEO volatility — the highest ceiling.
- Localized pages open entirely new ad/affiliate markets.

### Exit criteria
- Tier-3 pages releasing in a controlled, measured cadence with a working prune loop.
- API live with paying users.
- At least one additional locale live and indexed.

### Out of scope
- Mass-dumping thousands of pages at once (still forbidden). Buying links (always forbidden).

### Risks
- **Programmatic over-expansion** re-triggering thin-content demotion — the batch + prune discipline is the safeguard; never abandon it.

